"# Appendix A — ASCII diagram library

Every diagram used in the chapters, redrawn in one place for easy
reference. Flip here when you want to see the shape without the
surrounding prose.

Diagrams are laid out for monospaced terminals. On a proportional-font
viewer they may look crooked. Read them in `cat` or `less` or a
monospaced markdown viewer.

## A.1 Tally marks

```
     |    |    |
     |    |    |
   //|  //|  //|   .
    /|   /|   /|  /|
     |    |    |   |
     |    |    |   |
```

Groups of five with the diagonal cross-stroke. Reading a big count is
easier when grouped.

## A.2 Abacus (showing 42)

```
   thousands   hundreds   tens     ones
   ----------  --------   ------   ------
     .          .            *       * *
     .          .            *
     .          .            *
     .          .            *
     .          .
   ==========================================
     .          .          . . . .   . . .
     .          .          . . . .   . . .
```

Beads pushed up above the divider count. Divider is `====`.

## A.3 AND gate symbol

```
   A ---+---\\
        |    )---- Out
   B ---+---/
```

Flat back, round front. No bubble.

## A.4 OR gate symbol

```
   A ---+---\\\\
        |    ))---- Out
   B ---+---//
```

Curved back, pointed front. No bubble.

## A.5 NOT gate (inverter)

```
   A ---|>o---- Out
```

Triangle with a bubble on the point. The bubble is the invert.

## A.6 NAND gate

```
   A ---+---\\
        |    )-o---- Out
   B ---+---/
```

AND with a bubble on the output.

## A.7 NOR gate

```
   A ---+---\\\\
        |    ))-o---- Out
   B ---+---//
```

OR with a bubble on the output.

## A.8 XOR gate

```
   A ---+---\\\\\\
        |    \\\\)---- Out
   B ---+---///
```

OR with an extra curve on the back. Reads: exactly one input high.

## A.9 Half-adder

```
   A ---+--------+---\\
        |        |    ) XOR ---- sum
        |     +--+---/
        |     |
        |     +---+---\\
        |         |    ) AND ---- carry
   B ---+---------+---/
```

Two gates, two outputs. Sum is XOR. Carry is AND.

## A.10 Full-adder

```
                   +----------+
   A ------+-----> |          |          +----------+
           |       |  half-   |----s1--> |          |
           |       |  adder 1 |          |  half-   |----sum
   B ------+-----> |          |          |  adder 2 |
                   |          |----c1--+ |          |----c2--+
                   +----------+        | +----------+        |
                                       |    Cin --->         |
                                       |                     |
                                       +----+---\\            |
                                            |    )-OR-------+---> Cout
                                            +---/                |
                                                                 |
                                              c1-----------------+
```

Two half-adders plus an OR for the carry out.

## A.11 4-bit ripple-carry adder

```
     A3 B3         A2 B2         A1 B1         A0 B0
      | |           | |           | |           | |
      v v           v v           v v           v v
   +------+      +------+      +------+      +------+
   | full |<--Cin| full |<--Cin| full |<--Cin| full |<--- Cin (0)
   |adder |      |adder |      |adder |      |adder |
   |  3   |      |  2   |      |  1   |      |  0   |
   +------+      +------+      +------+      +------+
      | |           | |           | |           | |
      v v           v v           v v           v v
     Cout S3       Cout' S2       Cout'' S1     Cout''' S0
      |
      v
    Cout (final)
```

Four full-adders chained. Carry ripples right to left.

## A.12 SR latch (cross-coupled NANDs)

```
   S ---+---\\
        |    )-o---+------- Q
        |   /       |
        +--/        |
                    |
        +----+------+ (feedback)
        |
   +---/         (feedback)
   |   \\    +----+
   +----)-o-+---+---- Q-bar
       /        |
   R --+        |
                +---- (feedback into left NAND)
```

Two NANDs cross-wired. One bit of memory. Set by pulsing S. Reset by
pulsing R.

## A.13 D flip-flop (as a block)

```
   D ------+---> D flip-flop ---+---> Q
           |                    |
   CLK --->+  (samples D on     +---> Q-bar
              rising edge)
```

Sample D on the rising edge of CLK. Hold between edges.

## A.14 8-bit register

```
             CLK ---+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+----+
                    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |
                    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v
   D0 ------------> [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF] [FF]
   D1 ------------->
   ...
   D7 ---------------------------------->
                    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |    |
                    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v    v
                    Q0   Q1   Q2   Q3   Q4   Q5   Q6   Q7
```

Eight D flip-flops sharing a clock. Loads all bits together.

## A.15 4-bit ripple counter

```
   CLK --->[T]--- Q0 ---+--->[T]--- Q1 ---+--->[T]--- Q2 ---+--->[T]--- Q3
           |            |    |            |    |            |    |
           |            +----+ (Q0 acts   +----+ (Q1 acts   +----+ (Q2 acts
           |                    as clock       as clock       as clock
           +------ ...           for [T]1)      for [T]2)      for [T]3)
```

Each T flip-flop toggles on the falling edge of its clock. First
clock is external. Others are the previous stage's output.

## A.16 Multiplexer (4-to-1)

```
   In-0 ----+
            |
   In-1 ----+----->[MUX]------> Output
            |         ^
   In-2 ----+         |
            |       Select
   In-3 ----+       (2 bits)
```

Select picks which input to pass through. 2-bit select for 4 inputs.

## A.17 State diagram — traffic light (Moore)

```
       tick             tick
     +------> GREEN --------> YELLOW ---+
     |                                  |
     |                                  v
    RED <--------------------- tick <---+
```

Three states, one input (`tick`), output determined by state.

## A.18 State diagram — vending machine (Mealy, abbreviated)

```
                +5c/none         +10c/none        +5c/none
   HAVE-0 -----------> HAVE-5 -----------> HAVE-15 -------> HAVE-20
```

Arrows labelled `input/output`. Same state, different output on
different input. That is Mealy.

## A.19 CPU fetch-decode-execute loop

```
         +-------------------------+
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Fetch    |                   |
   |  (mem@PC) |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  PC += 1  |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Decode   |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Execute  |                   |
   |  (ALU op) |                   |
   +-----------+                   |
         |                         |
         v                         |
   +-----------+                   |
   |  Writeback|                   |
   +-----------+-------------------+
```

Every instruction is one turn of this loop. Every computer running.

## A.20 ALU block

```
     A       B        opcode
     |       |          |
     v       v          |
   +-----+-----+-----+ |
   | ADD | AND | OR  | |
   +-----+-----+-----+ |
     |     |     |     |
     v     v     v     v
     +------ MUX -------+---> Result
                        |
                        +---> flags (zero, carry, ...)
```

Compute everything in parallel; MUX selects the right answer.

## A.21 Memory hierarchy

```
   Registers
   |
   L1 cache
   |
   L2 cache
   |
   L3 cache
   |
   DRAM
   |
   SSD
   |
   Disk / tape / cloud
```

Fastest and smallest at the top. Slowest and largest at the bottom.

## A.22 TCP/IP layer stack

```
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Application (HTTP, SMTP, SSH)   |
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Transport (TCP or UDP)          |
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Internet (IP)                   |
   +-----------------------------------+
   |   Link (Ethernet, WiFi)           |
   +-----------------------------------+
```

Every packet climbs up on receive, down on send.

## A.23 Transformer inference loop (Book of ML cross-reference)

```
   +---------------------------------------+
   |                                       |
   v                                       |
   Tokens so far --> embed --> transformer -+> logits --> sample --> append
                                                                     |
                                                                     +---> next token
```

Book of ML chapter 16 builds this in Motoi Scheme.

## A.24 The 20,000-year arc

```
   Bone     Abacus    Boole   Shannon  Transistor  IC     CPU    Internet   LLM
    |         |         |        |         |        |      |        |         |
    v         v         v        v         v        v      v        v         v
  ~18kBC    ~3kBC    1854     1937      1947     1958   ~1970s   1969-...   2020s
```

One line. One arrow per epoch. That is this book.
")
